00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:09.300
and I'd started to meet people
that challenged my narrative.

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:12.780
So to support my family,
I opened a record store.

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:14.970
I still wasn't ready
or brave enough

00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:18.240
to leave behind that
community and that identity

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:20.220
because I had really
abandoned everything else,

00:13:20.220 --> 00:13:22.260
and my family was very new.

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:24.480
So I decided the
best way to find

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:27.420
a middle ground was
to get off the streets

00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:29.070
and open a record store.

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:31.017
That way, I could
support my family.

00:13:31.017 --> 00:13:32.850
That way, I could come
home in normal hours,

00:13:32.850 --> 00:13:35.262
and I wouldn't be
putting myself in danger.

00:13:35.262 --> 00:13:36.970
But the point of
opening the record store

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:40.770
was not just to sell music, it
was to sell white power music.

00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:43.140
So I began importing CDs--

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:46.410
this was before the
internet-- from Europe.

00:13:46.410 --> 00:13:51.450
And very, very quickly, it
became 75% of my gross revenue

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:52.380
at the store.

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:55.290
People were driving in from
California and New York

00:13:55.290 --> 00:13:59.040
to buy this white power music
because I was the only store

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:01.399
in the US selling it.

00:14:01.399 --> 00:14:02.940
Something else
happened at that time.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:06.690
I became a little bit
greedy as an entrepreneur,

00:14:06.690 --> 00:14:09.510
and I thought to myself,
why should I just take money

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:12.720
from my brothers and sisters
when I could be taking money

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:15.730
from the enemy as well?

00:14:15.730 --> 00:14:20.839
So I started to sell punk rock,
and hip hop, and heavy metal.

00:14:20.839 --> 00:14:22.380
And when the customers
came in to buy

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:28.310
that who were African-American
or Jewish or gay or Muslim,

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:30.164
at first, I was a
little standoffish.

00:14:30.164 --> 00:14:32.330
I was happy to take their
money, but I didn't really

00:14:32.330 --> 00:14:35.080
want to talk to them
or engage with them.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:38.660
But they kept coming back,
and they knew who I was.

00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:41.922
And I was confused why
they were supporting me.

00:14:41.922 --> 00:14:43.880
And every time they came
back, the conversation

00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:46.950
got to be a little
bit more personal.

00:14:46.950 --> 00:14:49.320
And then they would
come back, and then I

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:52.220
started asking them questions.

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:55.330
And one day, a black
teenager came in,

00:14:55.330 --> 00:15:00.650
and he had told me that his
mother had passed from cancer.

00:15:00.650 --> 00:15:03.680
And suddenly, I was able
to relate with this person

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:08.080
because my mother had been
diagnosed with cancer.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:11.630
And we connected
on a human level.

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:15.500
And then one day, a gay
couple came in with their son,

00:15:15.500 --> 00:15:18.080
and it was obvious how
much they loved him,

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:22.040
and it was the same love
that I felt for my child.

00:15:22.040 --> 00:15:25.370
And I began to realize that
we had more similarities

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:28.484
than differences, that I
had never in my life-- not

00:15:28.484 --> 00:15:30.650
just the eight years that
I was involved-- but never

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:35.090
in my life had a
meaningful conversation

00:15:35.090 --> 00:15:39.180
or interaction with
anybody who wasn't like me.

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:41.610
And because of my
store, I was now

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:44.880
having these meaningful
interactions with the people,

00:15:44.880 --> 00:15:47.160
who, in my head, I had a
different vision of who

00:15:47.160 --> 00:15:48.490
they were.

00:15:48.490 --> 00:15:49.770
I believed the propaganda.

00:15:49.770 --> 00:15:54.450
I believed the hate and the
lies and the scapegoating.

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:56.640
And now, suddenly, I
was meeting these people

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:01.650
for the first time, and
they showed me compassion.

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:05.750
They could have easily gone and
broken my windows at the store.

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:08.780
They could have easily gone and
threatened my family or harmed

00:16:08.780 --> 00:16:10.070
me, but they didn't.

00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:15.020
Even know they knew who I
was, they kept coming back.

00:16:15.020 --> 00:16:17.120
And I received compassion
from the people

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.990
that I least deserved it from
when I least deserved it.

00:16:20.990 --> 00:16:24.950
And that really allowed me
to humanize them and realize

00:16:24.950 --> 00:16:26.870
that we needed
each other, that we

00:16:26.870 --> 00:16:30.260
had the same fundamental
needs of joy and love,

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:35.120
that we had the same emotions
of anger and sadness,

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:38.300
and that we really were
all pieces of a puzzle that

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:40.900
couldn't be built
without each other.

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:43.810
So I became embarrassed to
sell the white power music,

00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:45.760
and I closed the
store, obviously,

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:48.250
because I couldn't
sustain it anymore

00:16:48.250 --> 00:16:50.650
with it being 75% of my revenue.

00:16:50.650 --> 00:16:53.950
And at that same moment,
when I closed my store,

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:57.710
my life fell apart.

00:16:57.710 --> 00:17:00.700
I didn't have a job anymore,
so my livelihood was gone.

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:02.920
My wife and my children
left me because I

00:17:02.920 --> 00:17:05.500
hadn't left the
movement quickly enough

00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:07.510
and paid attention to them.

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:10.300
I didn't have a great
relationship with my parents,

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:14.099
and I had lost my whole
community that I had built.

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:17.040
So suddenly, I was without that
identity and that community

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:18.619
and a purpose.

00:17:18.619 --> 00:17:22.829
And for the next five years,
I woke up every morning

00:17:22.829 --> 00:17:26.310
and I considered taking my
life because I wasn't sure

00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:27.000
how to proceed.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.680
I was treating other
people with respect.

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:35.210
I started to understand
our similarities,

00:17:35.210 --> 00:17:39.440
but I was still miserable inside
because, for those five years,

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:42.290
I tried to outrun who I was.

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:46.670
I tried to make new friends,
wasn't very successful at that.

00:17:46.670 --> 00:17:51.020
I moved, wore long sleeves
to cover my tattoos.

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:53.630
I was doing everything
I could to not face who

00:17:53.630 --> 00:17:56.570
I was because I was afraid
of being judged just like I

00:17:56.570 --> 00:18:00.980
judged other people until, one
day, at the end of that five

00:18:00.980 --> 00:18:04.410
years, a friend of mine
came up to me, and she said,

00:18:04.410 --> 00:18:07.960
you have to do something because
I don't want to lose you.

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:09.710
And I said, OK, well,
what do you suggest?

00:18:09.710 --> 00:18:11.520
And she said, well, I
just started working

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:13.350
at this company called IBM.

00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:14.970
You may have heard of them.

00:18:14.970 --> 00:18:16.470
Why don't you apply
for a job there?

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:18.120
And I said, you're crazy.

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:19.710
I said, I'm like an ex-Nazi.

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:21.250
I'm covered in tattoos.

00:18:21.250 --> 00:18:22.450
I went to six high schools.

00:18:22.450 --> 00:18:24.890
I get kicked out of all of
them-- one of them twice.

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:26.806
I didn't go to university,
oh, and by the way,

00:18:26.806 --> 00:18:29.580
I don't own a computer or
know how to use a computer.

00:18:29.580 --> 00:18:31.350
Why would they hire me?

00:18:31.350 --> 00:18:33.570
And she said, just go in
there for an interview.

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:36.360
See what happens, and just tell
them you're good with people.

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:39.240
I was like, yeah, OK, that's
what I'm going to tell them.

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:41.130
But I wrote my resume.

00:18:41.130 --> 00:18:43.740
I lied on my resume.

00:18:43.740 --> 00:18:48.090
And I went in,
and I got the job.

00:18:48.090 --> 00:18:53.760
And that essentially
changed my life again

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:57.480
because now I had
found purpose again.

00:18:57.480 --> 00:19:03.440
That gave me the ability
to find the confidence

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.800
to approach other people,
to seek forgiveness,

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:09.620
but also to find a way to
forgive myself because I

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:12.090
had been unable to do that.

00:19:12.090 --> 00:19:14.800
And things started
to get better.

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:17.107
And the first day at IBM--

00:19:17.107 --> 00:19:18.940
of course, they have
millions of customers--

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:21.170
where did they put me?

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:23.720
Back at my old high school
for a computer rollout--

00:19:23.720 --> 00:19:26.480
the same high school I'd
been kicked out of twice.

00:19:26.480 --> 00:19:30.830
That was my first day
at my first job at IBM.

00:19:30.830 --> 00:19:33.450
I was terrified,
absolutely terrified.

00:19:33.450 --> 00:19:36.860
I was a grown man who
was sweating and shaking,

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:38.120
and I couldn't find the words.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:39.950
I was scared to walk
into the building

00:19:39.950 --> 00:19:41.366
because I was
afraid that somebody

00:19:41.366 --> 00:19:44.300
was going to say we know him.

00:19:44.300 --> 00:19:46.790
He's got to go, and I
would lose that opportunity

00:19:46.790 --> 00:19:48.460
for that first meaningful thing.

00:19:48.460 --> 00:19:51.872
And of course, on that
first day, who walks by me

00:19:51.872 --> 00:19:54.330
but the old black security
guard that I got in a fist fight

00:19:54.330 --> 00:19:58.180
with that got me kicked
out for the second time?

00:19:58.180 --> 00:20:00.010
I really didn't know
what to do then,

00:20:00.010 --> 00:20:02.180
but I decided I had
to do something.

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:05.260
I knew I couldn't live in
that fear of being found

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:06.640
out or recognized and fired.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:10.152
So I decided I was going to
chase him to the parking lot--

00:20:10.152 --> 00:20:11.860
probably not the
smartest thing for a guy

00:20:11.860 --> 00:20:13.193
that I got in a fist fight with.

00:20:13.193 --> 00:20:15.932
But when I saw him
getting into his car,

00:20:15.932 --> 00:20:17.140
I tapped him on the shoulder.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:20.560
And this man, who normally
had this beautiful jolly

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:24.370
smile, when he turned
around and recognized me,

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:28.820
he took a step back
because he was afraid.

00:20:28.820 --> 00:20:34.410
I couldn't think of what
to say except I'm sorry.

00:20:34.410 --> 00:20:38.250
And I stuck out my
hand, and he shook it.

00:20:38.250 --> 00:20:40.660
And we talked.

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:44.072
We embraced, may have
cried just a little bit.

00:20:44.072 --> 00:20:45.030
It was a long time ago.

00:20:45.030 --> 00:20:46.840
I'm not really sure.

00:20:46.840 --> 00:20:49.630
I'm pretty sure we cried.

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:52.160
But after talking, he
made me make a promise,

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:56.900
and that promise was that I
would tell the world my story,

00:20:56.900 --> 00:21:00.470
not because he thought, oh, kids
are going to become neo-Nazis.

00:21:00.470 --> 00:21:01.460
You should tell them.

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.160
But because he recognized,
in my story, the story

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:07.190
of every young person,
who is vulnerable,

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:10.880
who is marginalized,
who can very easily find

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:12.902
a destructive path.

00:21:12.902 --> 00:21:17.250
And I didn't really know what
he meant until a couple years

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:22.980
later, and I got a phone call in
2004 in the middle of the night

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:27.470
that my younger brother
had been shot and killed.

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:32.240
And then I knew that I had
to tell my story because he

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:35.430
was driving in a car
with some friends

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:37.960
in a neighborhood
he wasn't used to,

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:41.690
and some kids who are
scared of his skin color

00:21:41.690 --> 00:21:45.140
decided that they were
going to shoot into the car.

00:21:45.140 --> 00:21:47.840
And I knew that this wasn't
just something that affected me.

00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:49.550
I knew then, at
this time, that I

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:51.650
wasn't the only one
with this problem,

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:54.500
that there were a lot
of lost young people

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:57.980
who needed to understand that
there was a more positive path.

00:21:57.980 --> 00:22:00.740
So it took me 10 years to
do it, but eventually, I

00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:03.770
wrote and published my book.

00:22:03.770 --> 00:22:06.680
And in my book, I speak
to every young person.

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:11.130
While I use my own story,
and I tell my story,

00:22:11.130 --> 00:22:13.080
I use the language
that I used at that age

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:14.790
because I want other
young people to be

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:16.710
able to relate to
what I went through,

00:22:16.710 --> 00:22:20.520
and I think that I was
successful with that.

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:22.620
I also co-founded an
organization called

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:25.890
Life After Hate, and everybody
you see in this picture

00:22:25.890 --> 00:22:29.850
here is a former
extremist, who has been out

00:22:29.850 --> 00:22:31.590
for at least the
last 20 years and has

00:22:31.590 --> 00:22:34.620
dedicated their lives
to helping dismantle

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:36.720
what they helped build.

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:40.620
For the last 22 years of my
life, mostly for the last 15,

00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:43.110
I've been very actively
engaged in helping

00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:46.770
people understand the
movement that I helped build.

00:22:46.770 --> 00:22:50.020
I've consulted with
law enforcement

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:52.150
and done public speaking.

00:22:52.150 --> 00:22:53.980
But most of all, what
I'm the most proud of

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:58.439
is helping people disengage
from hate and hate groups.

00:22:58.439 --> 00:22:59.980
And we're able to
be successful doing

00:22:59.980 --> 00:23:03.400
that because we really relate to
the people we're working with.

00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:07.270
We were those people at
one point in our lives.

00:23:07.270 --> 00:23:12.340
And what we do, when we work
with people, is we listen.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:15.160
And we listen for
what I call potholes.

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:17.140
Potholes are the
things that appeared

00:23:17.140 --> 00:23:20.320
in your path that happened to
you that eventually deviated

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:22.366
you onto a different path.

00:23:22.366 --> 00:23:23.740
And when I listen
for potholes, I

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:29.900
hear about trauma and abuse,
poverty, lack of education,

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:32.270
mental illness.

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:36.600
And my job, then, becomes
to fill those potholes.

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:38.430
I work with partners
all over the country

00:23:38.430 --> 00:23:42.210
to bring mental health
support, or job training,

00:23:42.210 --> 00:23:46.410
or career guidance,
or education, even

00:23:46.410 --> 00:23:50.100
tattoo removal for people, who
are in these movements, who

00:23:50.100 --> 00:23:51.040
want to get out.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:53.040
And I tell you that there
are so many people who

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:55.200
are stuck in these movements,
and even though they

00:23:55.200 --> 00:23:57.780
may be questioning
their ideology,

00:23:57.780 --> 00:24:00.900
they don't leave because they've
already abandoned everything

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:02.220
to go back to.

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:05.310
And they've spent time and
energy building this community

00:24:05.310 --> 00:24:09.000
and this identity that starting
over is very, very difficult.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:10.830
And I know because I was there.

00:24:10.830 --> 00:24:13.290
So we try to be this
new community for them.

00:24:13.290 --> 00:24:16.440
We've actually built a
network of over 200 people

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:19.380
that we've helped leave,
that have found us

00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:20.250
after they've left.

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:25.340
And we provide a virtual
support system for them.

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:28.370
They can talk to each other
and understand each other.

00:24:28.370 --> 00:24:31.850
And some days, in our
virtual community--

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:33.620
it's cat memes and
joking around--

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:35.810
and some days, it
gets really heavy,

00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:38.960
where somebody will admit
for the first time to anybody

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:42.110
that they were sexually
abused at three years old,

00:24:42.110 --> 00:24:44.720
or they'll come
online and tell us

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:48.290
that their son committed
suicide that morning.

00:24:48.290 --> 00:24:50.030
And we rally.

00:24:50.030 --> 00:24:52.460
We surround that person with
love and with compassion

00:24:52.460 --> 00:24:56.940
and empathy, and they make it
because sometimes the things

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.070
that they're going through
because of their past--

00:24:59.070 --> 00:25:00.444
it's not something
that they feel

00:25:00.444 --> 00:25:03.000
comfortable talking about
with other people that

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:03.980
haven't experienced it.

00:25:06.706 --> 00:25:08.830
I just want to talk a little
bit about the movement

00:25:08.830 --> 00:25:12.800
now because it's changed
over the last 30 years.

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:14.960
What we used to think of
when we thought of the far

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:17.420
right extremist movement--

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:22.852
we think of skinheads
and Klan and militia.

00:25:22.852 --> 00:25:24.810
And there are still people
out there like that.

00:25:24.810 --> 00:25:27.150
We see them on the
news from time to time,

00:25:27.150 --> 00:25:29.330
but it's different now.

00:25:29.330 --> 00:25:33.050
The internet has changed things.

00:25:33.050 --> 00:25:34.640
And this is an
important topic for me,

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:36.431
and I'm glad I'm speaking
to you about this

00:25:36.431 --> 00:25:40.790
because, obviously, you are at
the fore of this thing called

00:25:40.790 --> 00:25:45.310
the internet and connecting
people and information.

00:25:45.310 --> 00:25:48.280
But what I've seen lately,
because of the internet,

00:25:48.280 --> 00:25:51.100
is that so many vulnerable
young people, who

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:53.920
may be socially
awkward in real life,

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:55.810
are finding their identity
in their community

00:25:55.810 --> 00:25:59.830
online in not the
greatest of places.

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:02.950
I'm seeing so much
propaganda and fake

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:08.110
news that is directing these
young people to a new narrative

00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:11.050
