00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:49.460
AUDIENCE: Hi, Christian.

00:41:49.460 --> 00:41:50.120
Great talk.

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:51.570
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: Hi.

00:41:51.570 --> 00:41:56.450
AUDIENCE: What is your take
on this casual kind of racism

00:41:56.450 --> 00:41:57.740
we're seeing that--

00:41:57.740 --> 00:41:59.900
it's not exactly
punching in the face,

00:41:59.900 --> 00:42:02.360
and it's not exactly dressing
up and going to college

00:42:02.360 --> 00:42:03.800
as a racist or
running for office,

00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:07.970
but it's like this kind
of lame, casual commenting

00:42:07.970 --> 00:42:10.940
that I see even teens--

00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:14.340
people we wouldn't assume to
be like this anymore-- doing?

00:42:14.340 --> 00:42:17.450
What do you think about that,
or how do we change something

00:42:17.450 --> 00:42:18.470
like that?

00:42:18.470 --> 00:42:20.011
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI:
First of all, I

00:42:20.011 --> 00:42:22.520
think it was likely
always there, right?

00:42:22.520 --> 00:42:24.530
It was probably dormant,
lived in the shadows,

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:29.120
and because of our political
climate, a lot of people

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:30.800
feel emboldened
saying those things

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:34.280
because, frankly, a lot
of people at the top

00:42:34.280 --> 00:42:38.540
are saying very, very
similar things, right?

00:42:38.540 --> 00:42:40.850
It's shaped to be a
little bit more palatable.

00:42:40.850 --> 00:42:43.430
The messaging is a
little bit different,

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:44.940
but the mission is the same.

00:42:44.940 --> 00:42:47.270
And I know because this
is the ball that we

00:42:47.270 --> 00:42:49.060
started to roll 30 years ago.

00:42:49.060 --> 00:42:52.700
And as far as the
casual comments,

00:42:52.700 --> 00:42:54.950
I don't engage in them.

00:42:54.950 --> 00:42:59.840
If I do engage, I engage in
a very compassionate way.

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:04.010
And it's hard for people
to shut down compassion.

00:43:04.010 --> 00:43:06.062
However, if you
attack back, you're

00:43:06.062 --> 00:43:07.770
going to see it just
go on and on and on,

00:43:07.770 --> 00:43:10.610
and you'll see the
polarization go even wider.

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:12.770
Have honest conversations
with people.

00:43:12.770 --> 00:43:16.280
Don't necessarily seriously
challenge their narrative.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:17.900
Just be the message.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:20.730
Be the message that
you want them to be.

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:22.830
So if you want them
to be understanding,

00:43:22.830 --> 00:43:24.500
you have to show understanding.

00:43:24.500 --> 00:43:27.920
If you want them to be
compassionate or empathetic,

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:29.730
that's something you
have to do first.

00:43:29.730 --> 00:43:31.750
So that applies to
strangers, and I

00:43:31.750 --> 00:43:33.920
think it applies
to people that they

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:36.350
might be family members that
we block on social media

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:37.850
sometimes.

00:43:37.850 --> 00:43:40.130
But I think that we have to
establish that connection.

00:43:40.130 --> 00:43:42.710
We have to start by
finding a middle ground

00:43:42.710 --> 00:43:46.187
and then go out and talk about
all the difficult things.

00:43:46.187 --> 00:43:48.020
But we have to have
these difficult and very

00:43:48.020 --> 00:43:49.520
awkward conversations.

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:51.810
That's what's going
to connect us again.

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:55.450
Thank you, Sunni.

