00:44:46.600 --> 00:44:49.620
so if there's like one
person in particular-- just

00:44:49.620 --> 00:44:52.795
to kind of understand
the support.

00:44:52.795 --> 00:44:53.920
CHRISTIAN PICCIOLINI: Sure.

00:44:53.920 --> 00:44:57.220
First of all, those five
years were really dark.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:44:59.170
I didn't have a steady job.

00:44:59.170 --> 00:45:02.350
I didn't date.

00:45:02.350 --> 00:45:05.200
I was still very adamant about
being there for my children

00:45:05.200 --> 00:45:07.400
that I saw every weekend,
but other than that,

00:45:07.400 --> 00:45:10.180
the rest of those five
days, I was deteriorating.

00:45:10.180 --> 00:45:13.990
I got into drugs and
alcohol, and I was just

00:45:13.990 --> 00:45:16.660
really not treating myself
with a whole lot of respect.

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:20.170
I was really ashamed of
what I had been through,

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:22.960
and I didn't think that
I deserved happiness.

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:24.940
So I was really
going out of my way

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:27.670
to be extra kind and extra
compassionate to other people,

00:45:27.670 --> 00:45:30.115
but I was completely
ignoring myself.

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:35.890
The second question--
there were a lot of people.

00:45:35.890 --> 00:45:37.277
It wasn't just one instance.

00:45:37.277 --> 00:45:38.860
There were so many--
it was like I was

00:45:38.860 --> 00:45:40.590
a pinball in a pinball machine.

00:45:40.590 --> 00:45:43.450
It was like everybody
that I touched somehow

00:45:43.450 --> 00:45:46.990
would impart on me
some sort of wisdom.

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:49.630
And I would take just like
a nugget from everybody,

00:45:49.630 --> 00:45:52.660
and eventually I was able
to put them all together.

00:45:52.660 --> 00:45:57.370
When I stopped the ego, when
I stopped thinking and started

00:45:57.370 --> 00:46:01.690
feeling, that's really when
I connected with who I was

00:46:01.690 --> 00:46:04.480
and with the innocence
that I lost at 14 years old

00:46:04.480 --> 00:46:07.180
because I went from this
13 and 1/2 year old kid

00:46:07.180 --> 00:46:10.120
to this 14-year-old
monster, essentially.

00:46:10.120 --> 00:46:13.180
I was doing things that, not
only most adults don't do,

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:15.910
but most people wouldn't do.

00:46:15.910 --> 00:46:18.370
So it was a very difficult time.

00:46:18.370 --> 00:46:23.500
And leaving that, I didn't
have any relapses because one--

00:46:23.500 --> 00:46:24.340
I couldn't go back.

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:27.385
Once I left, there's
no going back.

00:46:27.385 --> 00:46:31.799
And two-- I knew how it made
me feel when I was there.

00:46:31.799 --> 00:46:34.090
And even though I was going
through a miserable period,

00:46:34.090 --> 00:46:39.580
and it was a very dark time,
I still felt some peace

00:46:39.580 --> 00:46:41.080
that I wasn't involved in that.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:46.660
And I knew I didn't want
to stir up those feelings

00:46:46.660 --> 00:46:48.160
or go back into that confusion.

00:46:48.160 --> 00:46:51.760
I knew, at that time, it was
not something I wanted to do.

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:54.172
And pretty quickly
after those five years,

00:46:54.172 --> 00:46:56.380
I started the ball rolling
and doing some of the work

00:46:56.380 --> 00:46:58.690
that I do now and
writing my book.

00:46:58.690 --> 00:47:00.700
And writing my book, I
tell you, for 10 years--

00:47:00.700 --> 00:47:03.640
really, it was pretty cathartic.

00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:06.370
It was pretty therapeutic for
me to even think about some

00:47:06.370 --> 00:47:09.820
of the things that I'd
forgotten about myself.

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:14.450
So it's almost like self-therapy
for me to write the book.

00:47:14.450 --> 00:47:15.770
It was a tough time.

00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:18.340
I'm glad I made it past that.

00:47:18.340 --> 00:47:18.977
Yes?

